54–Deceased","1225–1280":"1225–1280","about 1280":"about 1280","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Llanddewi, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Llandewi, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales","Llandow, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llandow, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Welsh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Walsh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Dermot, John Patrick, Kieran, Declan, Eamonn, Colm, Donal, Seamus, Siobhan, Brennan.","English and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>walshe</i> (Old English <i>wælisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’. This form of the name was generally more common than   Welsh  , especially in Ireland, where it originally denoted a Welsh-speaking immigrant, in particular any of the Welshmen who arrived in the wake of Strongbow's Anglo-Norman invasion of 1170. In Ireland it is sometimes also a translation of <b>Breathnach</b> ‘Briton’.","English: in Yorkshire and Lancashire the name is sometimes a shortened form of   Walshaw  ."]},{"name":"Walch","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Welsh  .","German: from the personal name <i>Walcho</i>.","German: ethnic name, a variant of   Wahl   1."]},{"name":"Wilch","meanings":["German (Hesse and Rhineland-Palatinate): unexplained.","English: apparently a variant of   Welsh  ."]},{"name":"Welch","meanings":["English: variant of   Welsh   or   Walsh  , an ethnic name for someone of Welsh origin. This is the usual form of the surname in England; the usual form in Ireland is   Walsh   and in Scotland   Welsh  .","German: variant of   Welk  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]},{"name":"Welshans","meanings":["Irish: derivative of   Welsh  , with Irish diminutive <i>-an</i> and English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Welsh was born in 1225, in Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales. He had at least 2 daughters with Mrs. John Welsh. He died about 1280, in Wales, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1225–about 1280":"1225–umbes 1280","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1225–1280":"1225–1280","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Llanddewi, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Llandewi, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales","Llandow, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llandow, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"1225–about 1280":"1225–noin 1280","1229–Female":"1229–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1254–Female":"1254–Kuollut","1225–1280":"1225–1280","about 1280":"noin 1280","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Llanddewi, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales","Llandewi, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Llanddewi, Glamorgan, Wales","Llandow, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llandow, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"1225–about 1280":"1225–environ 1280","1229–Female":"1229–Décédée","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1254–Female":"1254–Décédée","1225–1280":"1225–1280","about 1280":"environ 1280","1225":"1225","1254":"1254","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1229":"1229","Llanddewi, G